@Controller ---> Used for traditional web applications. It returns a web page (HTML/View).
@RestController ---> Used for modern APIs. It returns raw data (JSON or XML) directly to the body of the HTTP response.
    @RestController = @Controller + @ResponseBody
@RequestMapping = It maps an incoming web request (URL) to a specific Java method in your code.
    @GetMapping = Fetch data (Read) = @RequestMapping(value = "/profile", method = RequestMethod.GET)
    @PostMapping = Send new data (Create) = @RequestMapping(value = "/profile", method = RequestMethod.POST)
    @PutMapping = Update existing data (Update) = @RequestMapping(value = "/path", method = RequestMethod.PUT)
    @DeleteMapping = Remove data (Delete) = @RequestMapping(value = "/profile", method = RequestMethod.DELETE)

LomBok
    Its sole purpose is to eliminate boilerplate code—the repetitive, tedious lines of code that Java forces you to write 
    but adds no real logic (like getters, setters, constructors, and toString() methods).

        without LomBok
        public class User {
            private Long id;
            private String name;
            private String email;

            // Boilerplate Constructor
            public User(Long id, String name, String email) {
                this.id = id;
                this.name = name;
                this.email = email;
            }
            public User() {}

            // Boilerplate Getters and Setters
            public Long getId() { return id; }
            public void setId(Long id) { this.id = id; }
            public String getName() { return name; }
            public void setName(String name) { this.name = name; }
            public String getEmail() { return email; }
            public void setEmail(String email) { this.email = email; }

            // Boilerplate toString, equals, and hashCode... (another 20 lines!)
        }

        with LomBok
        import lombok.Data;

        import lombok.Data;
        import lombok.NoArgsConstructor;
        import lombok.AllArgsConstructor;

        @Data                // Automatically generates Getters, Setters, toString, equals, and hashCode!
        @NoArgsConstructor   // Automatically generates a blank constructor: public User() {}
        @AllArgsConstructor  // Automatically generates a full constructor with all fields
        public class User {
            private Long id;
            private String name;
            private String email;
        }
@Service ---> 
    Used to mark a class as the place where your business logic lives.
    It tells Spring: "Hey, this class is a specialized component that calculates, processes, and manages 
    data for the application. Please take control of it."
    Why?
        Keep Controllers Clean: Controllers should only handle web requests and status codes. 
            They shouldn't do math or database calculations.
        Reusability: If you write logic inside a @Service, you can reuse that exact same logic for a web browser request, 
            a mobile app request, or a scheduled background task.
        Component Scanning: By putting @Service at the top, Spring automatically finds the class when your app starts up, 
            creates an instance of it, and shares it wherever it's needed (Dependency Injection).

